ce:section.ce:para:
N, S co-doped carbon dots can be prepared readily using L-cysteine as starting material through hydrothermal synthesis method. The digital pictures of the aqueous dispersions indicate the good dispersion of NSCDs in aqueous solutions. The morphology and microstructure identified by the typical TEM image and XRD are shown in Fig. 1
                        . NSCDs are not very uniform in shape and their size is about 2.8–7.1nm with an average diameter of 4.7nm. This inhomogeneous size may result in the fluorescence of the NSCDs is excitation-dependent because the fluorescence characteristics of NSCDs may greatly depend on their size due to the quantum-confinement effect [55]. The high-resolution TEM(HRTEM)suggests that most particles possess a crystalline core with an amorphous surface. The crystalline core displays a lattice spacing distances of 3.4Å, similar to that of graphite (002) facets which indicates that NSCDs contain sp2-hybridized carbon. While the amorphous surface indicates that NSCDs contain sp3-hybridized carbon. X-ray diffraction (XRD) pattern of the NSCDs shows a broad peak centered at 23.9° which is attributed to their graphitic components, consistent to the HRTEM results. No obvious D or G bands is detected in Raman spectra of the NSCDs presumably due to high fluorescence disturbance [56]. FT-IR (Fig. 2
                        ) and X-ray photoelectron spectroscopy (XPS) (Fig. 3
                        ) were further performed to study the function groups and the chemical composition of the NSCDs. The broad absorption band at 3378cm−1 is assigned to stretching vibrations of OH, NH. It demonstrates that there are abundant amount of amino and hydroxyl groups on the NSCDs surface, which is favored to give the NSCDs good hydrophilic properties. The bands at 3169 and 1567cm−1 are attributed to the vibrational absorption band of CH and CC, while those around 1639 and 1402cm−1 associated with CO adjoining a conjugated structure and CN, respectively. The peak at 1048cm−1 is linked to the C=S vibration with weak CS stretching observed at 651cm−1. The full scan XPS spectrum of NSCDs is shown in Fig. 3 excluded presenting 3 peaks at 534, 399.4 and 287.5eV, which separately correspond to O 1s, N 1s and C 1s，there two peaks at 231and 167eV are probably resulted from S 1s and S 2p. Those observations demonstrate the successful doping of N and S in as-prepared NSCDs. The high resolution scans of the C1s region with three different peaks imply that carbon is in three different chemical states. The peak near 284.6eV suggests the presence of graphitic structure (sp2 CC) of the NSCDs. The peak at around 285.6eV can be attributed to sp3-bonded carbon with oxygen (CO), sulfur (CS) and nitrogen (CN), while that one centered at 288.2eV can be assigned to CO. The N 1s spectrum shows two peaks, centered at 400.8 and 399.1eV, each linked to the pyrrolic N (C-N-C) and NH bands. High resolution of the S 2p spectrum of NSCDs clearly exhibits three peaks, in which centered at163.7 and 166.4eV represent S 2p3/2 S-C and S-O, and that at 164.3eV associates with S 2p3/2 of thiophene consistent to the FTIR results.
